Asatru</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=nenjindarkeyes>Nenjin Darkeyes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/7/02 9:49:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22154.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Depressed?</span><hr size=1> Wow, never thought I would see the day when a topic like this made it onto a board.<br>
<br>
Yes, I know where you are coming from. Played EQ like a junky for almost a year and a half. Then I had some relationship problems(yes, EQ can even be sweeter than a GF...rarely) and once that was over, coming back to EQ as difficult. I started to get very depressed thinking about myself and hundreds of thousands of others hunched over their keyboards in a badly lit room, 6 to 8 hours a _weekday_. So I took some time off. I forsook EQ for almost 4 months. I didnt even bother to log back on to say hi to my guild. I hung out with friends, partied, got a job again, started going back to school ect....<br>
Then one day, I logged on, went to Gfay and bought something. Started talking with all the people in my guild again. And it felt really good. <br>
<br>
The moral that worked for me is this. EQ does not = Depression. EQ can intensify the feelings of loneliness ect....but it doesnt create them. You bring those feelings to EQ. Take some time off. Remember what its like to have a real life with flesh and blood people, get busy, and when the time comes, and you want to play again, you find that you enjoy gaming again for its ultimate value, its fun, diverting, and you meet online friends. When EQ is supplementing something that is missing in your life, that is when the depression starts.<br>
<br>
