<br>
If there's anything my psych teacher drilled into my head it was that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uvenvensilentdagger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Venven Silentdagger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/9/02 10:07:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22154.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re: Re:</span><hr size=1> Heh, I never thought such a topic as this would come up on any EQ board at all. It's pretty touchy.<br>
<br>
How I see it, is that EverQuest is a escape from reailty, an alternative 'world'. Maybe EverQuest is the place you are happiest in/with.<br>
<br>
Alot of factors comes in that can make you depressed, It's pretty hard to say what can make a person depressed sometimes. But I know depression exists in EverQuest, I see it daily, and It's pretty easy to notice people that are depressed, after having played since beta, I know a bunch of people. Some are very close friends, some are not as close.<br>
<br>
You gain friends, also enemies in this game. Everquest is a very social game. You chat alot, and you work together with other players all the time. Being solo in EverQuest does work but it isn't the most enjoyable thing to do, most people agree with this I bet. Also together, you can gain so much more.<br>
<br>
You see friends part away to go back to their Real Life, you even see friends die In Real Life, and if they we're close friends to you in-game you get sad over it. Having a friend in EverQuest leaving the game, actually makes me miss him/her alot. Now when I use the word 'friend' this isn't someone I've known for 1 week, and just spoken briefly to each time, but still liked the person at those times. Of course I would miss those people too, but a friend to me is someone you've known for quite sometime, and spent pretty much time together, and chatting. Now I'm only refering to EverQuest.<br>
<br>
What I think can make a person that wasn't depressed before EverQuest, but got depressed sometime during their time with EverQuest can be.. <br>
<br>
This person have been playing the game very long, he have gained alot of friends during this time. When one of his closest friends quit the game, which he only knew through the game, and maybe via email and/or ICQ, he starts to get a bit sad about this, and misses his friend. Time passes by, before this he was in a guild together with his friend and he mostly played in this guild because of this friend. He left this guild shortly after his friend had quit the game. Something he regret later, now being alone unguilded. At least with his friend he could skip school, and irl things because he knew he had someone to come to when playing EverQuest, he felt this was the place he was most happy with/in.<br>
<br>
Now the addiction takes place, he still can't skip EverQuest, because EverQuest and all factors and the rest that are there got a 'grip' of him. And he miss the several aspects of the game. Something he dosen't yet realise. Even that he says he will leave the game, he can't. Eventually he's away for some time but can't evade it, and one day he plays for a bit again and get all stuck into it again.<br>
<br>
Some more time passes by, he joins a new guild with several friends. This guild was recently formed and he starts to get to know it's members, he is already with several pretty close friends to him in the guild. He explores new areas of Norrath, he only have a vauge memory of his friends parting, and he enjoy the game as much as he did before, if not even more.<br>
<br>
He get on his firsts real big raids, and learn to define and work out tactics and strats for different kind of things, mob's etc.<br>
He are starting to play EverQuest even later and later during nights, not even bothering about it. Denying that he really is addicted or just 'have' to do 'that' and 'that'. Time goes. He play even more, building up friendships, discovering new things together with his guild and friends. Bounds are formed. IRL things are skipped because of EverQuest, he get generally tired during days, this cause him to skip school, or work or whatever he got.<br>
<br>
IRL friends finds him to be harder to 'reach' due to his constant playing of EverQuest, he skip invitations to party's etc IRL, also this time because of EverQuest, maybe some raid was scheduled, maybe he had decided to meet a friend to him in-game and do something that day or weekend.<br>
<br>
EverQuest starts to control the persons life and schedule/time.<br>
He still dosen't realise that this is something not so good, for his life and world as 'whole'. He is just simply more happy with EverQuest then anything else at the present time, all the social aspects, and fun things to do in EverQuest, is enough challenge and social communication/interaction for him.<br>
He is proud over his character, or toon or whatever you like to call it. EverQuest more and more have become his life, and IRL really dosen't matter to him. As long he got the cash and food etc to play.<br>
<br>
More time passes, new things are done, and discovered. More friendships are bound, some really really close ones.<br>
Then one day the guild-leader of his guild says he need to go on a 'vacation' for a few week's, let's say 2 week's. The officers in the guild take over the leadership, since the guild leader basically did everything before and the spirit of the guild was raised by 101% when he lead raids and such it kinda hurt to see him go away even for this short time. Well..<br>
<br>
The officers do their best, and there is still raids, not as intesive ones as before, the guild leader keep in-touch with the guild from distance where he is atm, but very rarely. This vacation later turns out to be a job he have to do, and he promise to come back very soon, those 2 week's becomes a month instead. The guild is hurt by this, and the guild leader never show'd up ever again. The officers to their best still, but the guild is doomed from this discovery of the guild leader. It slowly falls apart, and all friendships that are bound, well... some remain, many split up. Many of those players played only because of the guild. Many retire, some goes to other guilds etc. The guild still exists, but barely on by the name. A new guild leader is assigned, but it dosen't last. People tryed to keep the guild alive, raids we're still being done, but there's low turnout of players, many failures etc. People get frustrated and after some time the guild disbands.<br>
<br>
Now some people may say, this is just a game. Well sure it's 'just' a game. But as I said above, people (pretty many actually) prefer EverQuest over IRL and see it like an escape from reality.<br>
<br>
Anyway, this person continue to play, he miss his guild alot, and some of the friends that retired from EQ because of this. <br>
<br>
During all this time he have been in fights with his IRL girl friend, she dosen't like EverQuest, and she thinks he spend too much time on this game. Well, this guild disband upsets him, and he is even more upset this day when they fight over the game, and his priority of time which is totally '@#%$' up according to the GF. Well, this fight ends up pretty bad, and they split up.<br>
<br>
Now this person stands there, being without his girl friend, his IRL pretty much being 'inactive and evaded' because of EverQuest, and his guild and friends are mostly gone in the game as well. He starts to get a bit depressed with time...<br>
<br>
Enough rambling, food of thought <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
